<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12087g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12087g">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12087g"> 87(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> childhood / Knighthood / Manhood / Some day I&apos;ll ne a night</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The Anglo-Saxons distinguished the period between <mark>Childhood and Manhood</mark> by the term &lsquo;Cnihthade,&rsquo; <mark>Knighthood</mark>: a term which still continued to indicate the connexion between Youth and Chivalry, when Knights were styled &lsquo;Children,&rsquo; as in the historic song beginning, &ldquo;Child Rowland to the dark tower came:&rdquo; an excellent expression, no doubt; for <mark>every Boy and Youth is, in his mind and sentiments, a Knight</mark>, and essentially a Son of Chivalry.&rdquo; <small> Edward FitzGerald, <a name="EFMI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EFMI"><cite title="source">Miscellanies</cite></a> (1900) 73</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n12087g" href="n12all.htm#n12087g">N12 (VI.B.14):087(g)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
